{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ddb02c8c-99eb-4408-8fbd-eafd726b9bd1","content":"## .NET's x86-64 Baseline Was Raised\n\nStarting with .NET 10, Microsoft raised the minimum x86-64 architecture level from **v1** to **v2**. Your .NET 10 deployment may have already required this (or it was enforced more strictly in .NET 11). The v2 baseline mandates:\n\n| Instruction Set | Required Since |\n|---|---|\n| SSE3, SSSE3 | x86-64-v2 |\n| SSE4.1, SSE4.2 | x86-64-v2 |\n| POPCNT | x86-64-v2 |\n| CMPXCHG16B | x86-64-v2 |\n\n**Your 2012 hardware** — likely Intel Sandy/Ivy Bridge or AMD Bulldozer — *should* support v2. But if any node has an older CPU (e.g., pre-2009 Core 2 or early AMD without SSE4.2), it will fail with exactly that error.\n\n**To diagnose**, run on the failing node:\n\n```bash\n# Check which ISA extensions the CPU supports\ngrep -oP 'sse4_2|ssse3|popcnt' /proc/cpuinfo | sort -u\n```\n\nIf any of those three are missing, that CPU doesn't meet the v2 baseline.\n\n**Your other platforms are unaffected** — the Arm64 Surface Pro X and Raspberry Pi 4 have their own (unchanged) baselines.\n\n**Options:**\n1. **Replace the hardware** — any Intel ≥ Nehalem (2008) or AMD ≥ Bulldozer (2011) supports v2.\n2. **Stay on an older .NET version** on that specific node.\n3. **Build a custom runtime** from source with the v1 baseline restored (unsupported, not recommended for production).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"912bedd9-08fd-4f5a-b2ed-78433afa22dd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements, so I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 10 (and continuing in .NET 11), Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT instructions. However, let me think more carefully...\n\n\nActually, I need to be precise about the timeline: .NET 8 and earlier used x86-64 v1 baseline, while .NET 10 introduced the breaking change to x86-64-v2, requiring SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, and CMPXCHG16B. This means older hardware from around 2012 or earlier wouldn't support these newer instruction sets.\n\nLet me reconsider the hardware compatibility more carefully. Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge processors from 2011-2012 do support all the x86-64-v2 requirements, but older chips like Core 2 Duo (Penryn, 2008) only go up to SSE4.1, and AMD Phenom II (2009) has SSE4a but lacks SSE4.1/4.2 support. So while 2012-era hardware should be fine with x86-64-v2, anything significantly older would hit compatibility issues.\n\nNow I'm wondering if the user's actual problem is that .NET 11 raised the requirement further to x86-64-v3, which needs AVX, AVX2, and other newer instruction sets. But I'm not certain about .NET 11's specific requirements given my knowledge cutoff, so the most likely scenario is that the x86-64-v2 breaking change happened in .NET 10 as planned. So the x86-64-v2 requirement was likely introduced in .NET 11, which would explain why the code runs fine on .NET 10 but fails on older hardware—the runtime now demands instruction sets like SSE4.2 and POPCNT that 2012-era processors might not have.\n\nThough actually, Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge from that era should support v2 just fine. It's possible .NET 11 jumped straight to x86-64-v3, which requires AVX2—that wasn't available until Haswell in 2013, so 2012 hardware like Ivy Bridge would definitely fail that requirement.\n\nThe most likely explanation is that .NET raised its baseline instruction set requirement, probably from v1 to v2 or even to v3. The error message matches what the runtime produces when it detects an unsupported instruction set. For the ARM platforms like Surface Pro X and Raspberry Pi 4, this x86 baseline change wouldn't affect them at all.","outputTokens":2008,"requestId":"D818:3C6787:48FA20B:4FC317E:69F1623E"},"id":"9c953f1f-0984-4e84-ae5a-2b3fac90a11f","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:44:09.419Z","parentId":"185db746-8567-47cc-b22e-fc3f4f2a36fe"}
